<pdd-reason>Deterministic static contract-rule coverage matrix for prompts, with story-regression test traceability and cross-dev-unit story attribution.</pdd-reason>
<pdd-interface>
{
  "type": "module",
  "module": {
    "classes": [
      {"name": "RuleCoverage", "kind": "dataclass"},
      {"name": "CoverageResult", "kind": "dataclass"}
    ],
    "functions": [
      {"name": "build_coverage", "signature": "(path: Path, stories_dir=None, tests_dir=None, *, prompt_text=None, require_prompt_qualified_tests=False, story_map=None, global_story_registry=None) -> CoverageResult", "returns": "CoverageResult"},
      {"name": "build_coverage_directory", "signature": "(directory: Path, stories_dir=None, tests_dir=None) -> list[CoverageResult]", "returns": "list[CoverageResult]"}
    ]
  }
}
</pdd-interface>
<pdd-dependency>contract_ir_python.prompt</pdd-dependency>
<pdd-dependency>user_story_tests_python.prompt</pdd-dependency>
<pdd-dependency>story_regression_python.prompt</pdd-dependency>

% You are an expert Python engineer implementing deterministic contract coverage analysis for PDD.
% The generated module is pdd/coverage_contracts.py and is exposed through `pdd checkup coverage`.

<requirements>
- Build a rule-to-evidence matrix for `.prompt` files containing `<contract_rules>`.
- Do not call an LLM or execute tests; analysis is static and deterministic.
- Read story evidence from recursively discovered `story__*.md` files linked by
  `<!-- pdd-story-prompts: ... -->` metadata and their `## Covers` sections.
- Read test evidence from recursively discovered `test_*.py` files only when a
  test name, nearby comment, or first docstring line explicitly references a rule ID.
- Recognize canonical rule IDs with an optional single ASCII letter suffix in
  declarations and all explicit test-evidence forms. Preserve `R1` and `R1a` as
  distinct normalized IDs (`R1` and `R1A`). A docstring reference is explicit
  only when the ID is followed by `:` or `-`; incidental prose such as "uses R1"
  MUST NOT count as evidence.
- Read waivers from `<waivers>` blocks and `WAIVED W<N>` entries in `<coverage>`.
- Classify rules as `checked`, `story-only`, `test-only`, `unchecked`, `waived`,
  or `failed`, applying priority `waived > failed > checked > story-only >
  test-only > unchecked`.
- Treat prompts without `<contract_rules>` as legacy-safe: return no rules and no error.
- Directory scans must recurse over `*.prompt` files and skip `*_LLM.prompt`.
- Expose `build_coverage(path, stories_dir=None, tests_dir=None, *, prompt_text=None, require_prompt_qualified_tests=False, story_map=None, global_story_registry: Optional[set[str]] = None) -> CoverageResult`
  and `build_coverage_directory(directory, stories_dir=None, tests_dir=None) -> list[CoverageResult]`.
- Surface a story-keyed `has_regression_test` dimension per discovered user
  story: `true` when at least one collected pytest test claims the story via
  `@pytest.mark.story(story_id="<slug>")`, else `false`. Compute it by querying
  the `story_regression` traceability API (`tests_for_story` / `has_regression_test`),
  not by re-implementing pytest collection here.
- This dimension MUST be orthogonal and additive: it MUST NOT alter the rule-keyed
  statuses or their `test_R<n>`-derived priority
  (`waived > failed > checked > story-only > test-only > unchecked`).
- Report the two orphan directions as diagnostics: a story with no claiming test
  (`has_regression_test: false`) and a test claiming a nonexistent story (a
  `story_id` with no matching `story__<slug>.md`, surfaced as a validation warning).
- `CoverageResult` (and `as_dict()` / `summary`) MUST carry the per-story
  `has_regression_test` boolean alongside the rule list as a new per-story
  structure. Do NOT bolt it onto `RuleCoverage`, which stays rule-keyed.
- Cross-dev-unit support (issue #1769):
  - Add two fields to `RuleCoverage`: `is_cross_unit: bool = False` and
    `cross_unit_partners: list[str]` (default empty list). Include both in
    `as_dict()` output.
  - `build_coverage_directory` initializes a shared `global_story_registry: set[str]`
    (story slugs already counted globally) and passes it to every `build_coverage`
    call via the new `global_story_registry` kwarg.
  - Inside `build_coverage`: for each linked story, compute its slug
    (`story_path.stem[len("story__"):]`). If `global_story_registry` is provided and
    the slug is already in the registry, attribute the story to the rule's `stories`
    list so the link is visible, but do NOT count it as additional coverage evidence.
    If the slug is not yet in the registry, add it and count normally.
  - When `global_story_registry` is `None` (single-file mode), skip deduplication
    entirely to preserve backward compatibility for direct `build_coverage` calls.
  - After attributing stories, lazily import `story_is_cross_unit` and
    `get_all_dev_units_for_story` from `pdd.user_story_tests` to populate
    `is_cross_unit` and `cross_unit_partners` on each `RuleCoverage` whose
    `stories` list contains at least one cross-unit story.
</requirements>

<contract_rules>
R1 - Legacy prompts
When a prompt does not contain `<contract_rules>`, the analyzer MUST return an empty
legacy-safe result and MUST NOT fail.

R2 - Linked stories only
The analyzer MUST NOT count a story unless its prompt metadata links it to the
prompt being analyzed.

R3 - Explicit test references only
The analyzer MUST count test evidence only when it explicitly names a contract rule ID.

R4 - Waiver precedence
When a rule is waived, the analyzer MUST classify it as `waived` regardless of
other evidence.

R5 - Invalid evidence
When linked story or referenced test evidence is statically invalid, the analyzer
MUST classify that rule as `failed` and include the failure detail.

R6 - Orthogonal story-regression dimension
The per-story `has_regression_test` dimension MUST be reported alongside, and MUST
NOT change, the rule-keyed `status` values or their priority order.

R7 - Cross-unit story attribution
When a story is cross-unit (two or more entries in either `pdd-story-prompts` or
`pdd-story-dev-units` metadata), the analyzer MUST set `is_cross_unit=True` and
populate `cross_unit_partners` with all dev-unit names for that story. The story
filename MUST still appear in the `stories` list so the link remains visible.

R8 - No double-counting in directory mode
When `build_coverage_directory` is used, a story slug that has already been counted
for a previous prompt in the same directory scan MUST NOT be counted again as
independent coverage evidence for subsequent prompts. The story remains attributed
and visible in `stories`, but the coverage classification MUST NOT change due to the
already-counted story.

R9 - Single-file mode bypasses deduplication
When `build_coverage` is called directly without a `global_story_registry`
(i.e. `global_story_registry` is `None`), deduplication MUST be skipped entirely.
This preserves backward compatibility for existing callers.

R10 - Suffixed rule IDs remain distinct
The analyzer MUST retain an optional single-letter rule suffix across declaration
parsing and test evidence. For example, `R1` and `R1a` are separate rules and
`test_R1a_*` is evidence for `R1A`, never `R1`.

R11 - Directory evidence proves prompt ownership
Directory scans MUST require test evidence to name both the prompt and rule using
`<prompt-path>#<rule-id>`. A generic repository test name such as `test_R1_*` MUST
NOT be attributed to every prompt that declares `R1`. Direct single-file calls
retain their backward-compatible unqualified behavior unless the caller sets
`require_prompt_qualified_tests=True`. Apply the same ownership rule to the
syntax-error fallback scanner and validation failures; malformed unrelated tests
MUST NOT add evidence or mark a local rule failed.
</contract_rules>

<acceptance_tests>
- `pytest tests/test_coverage_contracts.py tests/commands/test_coverage.py -q` MUST pass.
- `pdd checkup coverage --json prompts/` MUST emit machine-readable coverage results.
- `pdd checkup coverage prompts/example_python.prompt` MUST render one row per rule.
- `pdd checkup coverage <prompt>` MUST report, per user story, whether an executable
  regression test exists (`has_regression_test`).
- `test_rule_coverage_is_cross_unit_default_false`: `RuleCoverage` default has `is_cross_unit=False` and `cross_unit_partners=[]`.
- `test_rule_coverage_as_dict_includes_cross_unit_fields`: `as_dict()` always includes `is_cross_unit` and `cross_unit_partners`.
- `test_build_coverage_sets_cross_unit_flag`: when a cross-unit story is linked, `build_coverage` returns a `RuleCoverage` with `is_cross_unit=True` and non-empty `cross_unit_partners`.
- `test_build_coverage_directory_deduplicates_cross_unit_story`: a cross-unit story linked to two prompts is counted once globally; the second prompt's rule does not gain independent coverage from the already-counted story.
- `test_build_coverage_single_file_no_deduplication`: calling `build_coverage` directly (no `global_story_registry`) counts the story normally without deduplication.
- `test_build_coverage_directory_story_slug_key`: deduplication uses the story filename stem after `story__` as the slug key, not the full path.
- A two-prompt regression fixture MUST prove that generic `test_R1_*` and
  `test_R2_*` functions do not bleed into either prompt during directory scans,
  while `module_a.prompt#R1a` is attributed only to module A.
</acceptance_tests>
